@section Testing Framework

@cindex testing framework
@cindex T-Lisp testing
The T-Lisp interpreter includes a built-in testing framework:

@table @code
@item (deftest @var{name} () @var{body})
Define a named test.
@item (test-run @var{name})
Run a specific test.
@item (test-run-all)
Run all defined tests.
@item (assert-true @var{expr})
Assert that @var{expr} is true.
@item (assert-false @var{expr})
Assert that @var{expr} is false.
@item (assert-equal @var{expected} @var{actual})
Assert equality.
@item (assert-not-equal @var{a} @var{b})
Assert inequality.
@item (assert-error @var{expr})
Assert that @var{expr} throws an error.
@item (defvar @var{name} @var{value})
Define a test variable.
@item (set! @var{name} @var{value})
Mutate a variable (only in test context).
@item (deftest-suite @var{name} () @var{body})
Define a test suite.
@end table

@section T-Lisp REPL

@cindex REPL
@cindex interactive evaluation
The standalone @command{tlisp} CLI provides a REPL, one-shot
evaluation, script execution, and a Bun-compiled binary target.  It
uses the same interpreter as the editor with a standalone runtime
profile for stdout/stdin, filesystem, process, and module-loading
primitives.

@example
bun run tlisp
bun run tlisp -- -e '(+ 1 2)'
bin/tlisp script.tlisp
bun run build:tlisp
./dist/tlisp -e '(+ 1 2)'
@end example

The REPL keeps definitions across inputs, supports multiline forms, and
provides @code{*1}, @code{*2}, and @code{*3} for recent results plus
@code{*e} for the last error:

@example
@group
tlisp> (+ 1 2 3)
6
tlisp> (car '(1 2 3))
1
tlisp> (string-append "hello" " " "world")
"hello world"
tlisp> (defun square (n) (* n n))
tlisp> (square 7)
49
@end group
@end example

For the complete T-Lisp language and API reference, see the
@cite{T-Lisp Reference Manual} (@file{tlisp.info}).

